{{unreferenced|date=June 2008}} {{Infobox Shinto shrine | name = {{nihongo|'''Oyama Shrine'''|尾山神社|Oyama-jinja}} | image =Kanazawa-C-2852.jpg | width = | caption =Main gate | type = | dedication = | founded = | closed = | founder = | priest = | location_map = Japan | coordinates ={{coord|36|33|59|N|136|39|19|E|type:landmark_region:JP|display=title,inline}} | reisai = | honden = | address = | phone = | website = }} [[Image:Oyama Shrine (Ishikawa).jpg|thumbnail|Oyama-jinja]] {{nihongo|'''Oyama Shrine'''|尾山神社|Oyama-jinja}} is a [[Shinto shrine]] in [[Kanazawa, Ishikawa]], [[Japan]].
The shrine was established in 1599, dedicated to [[Maeda Toshiie]] (the first load of [[Kaga Domain]]), in [[Mount Utatsu|Utatsu-yama]] (卯辰山), east of [[Kanazawa, Ishikawa|Kanazawa]]. It was moved to its present location in 1873 and renamed to '''Oyama-jinja'''. The main gate was constructed in 1875. This gate is a peculiar mix of traditional [[Art and architecture of Japan|Japanese]], [[Culture of China|Chinese]], and [[Architectural style|European]] religious [[Architecture|architectural]] elements. The gate is {{convert|25|m}} high including the [[lightning rod]]. The third floor is particular famous for its [[Netherlands|Dutch]] stained-glass windows. It is said that the third floor was also used as a [[lighthouse]]. The gate was designated an [[Important Cultural Properties of Japan|Important Cultural Asset]] on August 29, 1950.
