The shrine was established in 1599, dedicated to [[:en:Maeda Toshiie|Maeda Toshiie]] (the first lord of [[:en:Kaga Domain|Kaga Domain]]), in [[Mount Utatsu|Utatsu-yama]] (卯辰山), east of [[:en:Kanazawa|Kanazawa]]. It was moved to its present location in 1873 and renamed to '''Oyama-jinja'''. The main gate was constructed in 1875. This gate is a peculiar mix of traditional [[:en:Art and architecture of Japan|Japanese]], [[:en:Culture of China|Chinese]], and [[:en:Shinto architecture|European]] religious [[:en:Architecture|architectural]] elements. The gate is {{convert|25|m}} high including the [[:en:Lightning rod|Lightning rod]]. The third floor is particular famous for its [[Netherlands|Dutch]] stained-glass windows. It is said that the third floor was also used as a [[:en:en:Lighthouse|en:Lighthouse]]. The gate was designated an [[:en:Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Asset]] on August 29, 1950.
